 <a href="/content/keepassx-keeping-your-passwords-safe" class="imagecache imagecache-teaser imagecache-linked imagecache-teaser_linked"><img src="http://www.linuxjournal.com/files/linuxjournal.com/ufiles/imagecache/teaser/nodeimage/story/kp_logo_main.png" alt="KeePassX Logo" title=""  class="imagecache imagecache-teaser" width="100" height="100" /></a> 
  
  


      <h2 class="title">
      <a href="/content/keepassx-keeping-your-passwords-safe" title="KeePassX: Keeping Your Passwords Safe ">KeePassX: Keeping Your Passwords Safe </a>
    </h2>
  
  

  
      <div class="meta">
              <div class="submitted">
		By <a href="/users/anthony-dean" title="View user profile.">Anthony Dean</a>&nbsp;<!--|
		Jul 16, 2012 -->
     
      
              <div class="terms terms-inline"><ul class="links inline"><li class="taxonomy_term_207 first"><a href="/tag/desktop" rel="tag" title="">Desktop</a></li>
<li class="taxonomy_term_20 active"><a href="/tag/reviews" rel="tag" title="" class="active">Reviews</a></li>
<li class="taxonomy_term_31 last"><a href="/tag/security" rel="tag" title="">Security</a></li>
</ul></div>
      
  	 </div>
    </div>
  
  
    


  <div class="content">

    
    
            
                    <a href="/content/keepassx-keeping-your-passwords-safe" class="imagecache imagecache-teaser imagecache-linked imagecache-teaser_linked"></a>        
        

<p>
For a long time, my password tracking system was quite simplistic:
hope I remembered the right passwords for each site or record
them in an ordinary word-processor document. Such methods obviously
have great flaws. I might have a hard time remembering a password for an
infrequently used site, and a word-processor document isn't the most
secure place to store passwords.<span class="read-more"><a href="/content/keepassx-keeping-your-passwords-safe"> more>></a></span>
  </div>



  <ul class="links inline"><li class="comment_comments first last"><a href="/content/keepassx-keeping-your-passwords-safe#comments" title="Jump to the first comment of this posting.">19 comments</a></li>
